A. Biggest issue: your “exact spherical trig” path still rounds LHA

In calcSightReduction(), LHA is computed as:

let lha = Math.round(gha + lon);

That means even your direct trig fallback is not using the true fractional LHA. It is using a whole-degree LHA. That is acceptable only for table entry logic, not for an “exact” computational path. Later the code computes Hc and Zn from that rounded value.

Why this matters in practice:

For SR tables, whole-degree LHA is correct.

For direct trig, it should be:

trueLHA = gha + DR longitude

normalized to 0–360

not rounded

So at present, your “calculator” behaves closer to a tabular approximation than a full-precision computational reduction.

B. Tutorial text and code disagree on Zn quadrant rules

Your educational section says:

Northern hemisphere, LHA > 180° → Zn = 360° − Z

Northern hemisphere, LHA ≤ 180° → Zn = Z

Southern hemisphere, LHA > 180° → Zn = 180° + Z

Southern hemisphere, LHA ≤ 180° → Zn = 180° − Z

But the actual code in computeSRTable() uses:

if (latDir > 0) {
    zn = lha > 180 ? zVal : 360 - zVal;
} else {
    zn = lha > 180 ? 180 - zVal : 180 + zVal;
}

So your code and the instructional text are reversed.

That is a serious training issue, because a trainee may learn one rule while the calculator applies another.

C. Mixed use of DR position and chosen position is not clearly separated

You correctly derive chosen longitude for whole-degree LHA in the SR-table workflow. That is good. But in the overall code flow, the distinction between:

DR position

Chosen/Assumed position

Position used for Hc/Zn

Position used for plotting intercept

is not cleanly enforced everywhere.

For celestial navigation training, this must be explicit:

Ho belongs to the observation

Hc and Zn belong to the assumed/chosen position

intercept is then transferred from AP/DR accordingly

Right now the code teaches that idea, but the computation path is not separated cleanly enough.
